\begin{align}
& \begin{aligned}
& \text{Step 1: Multiply the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator}\\
& \frac{4}{\sqrt{108}+2\sqrt{12}+2\sqrt{27}}\left( \frac{\sqrt{108}-2\sqrt{12}+2\sqrt{27}}{\sqrt{108}-2\sqrt{12}+2\sqrt{27}} \right) & \\
& =\frac{4\left(\sqrt{108}-2\sqrt{12}+2\sqrt{27} \right)}{108+12+27-36-12-12} &
\end{aligned} \\
& \begin{aligned}
& \text{Step 2: Simplify the denominator by combining like terms}\\
& =\frac{4\left(\sqrt{108}-2\sqrt{12}+2\sqrt{27} \right)}{25} &
\end{aligned}
\end{align}
\end{answer}

The numerator can be further simplified by factoring out common factors:

\begin{align}
& =\frac{4\left(6\sqrt{3}-4\sqrt{3}+6\sqrt{3} \right)}{25} \\
& =\frac{4\left(8\sqrt{3} \right)}{25} \\
& =\frac{32\sqrt{3}}{25}
\end{align}

Therefore, the final simplified answer is $$\frac{32\sqrt{3}}{25}$$.

